{{Tab
|title= === MacOS ===
|image=[[File:Logo-apple-500x500.png|50px]]
|content=

'''1.''' Download USBImager based on your CPU architecture (choose one): 

* [https://gitlab.com/bztsrc/usbimager/-/raw/binaries/usbimager_1.0.10-arm-macosx-cocoa.zip Intel CPU]

* [https://gitlab.com/bztsrc/usbimager/-/raw/binaries/usbimager_1.0.10-intel-macosx-cocoa.zip Arm CPU (M1, M2 etc)].

'''2.''' Extract the ZIP archive to <code>/Applications</code>.

'''3.''' Run the USBImager application.

'''4.''' On the first row, insert the {{{project}}} {{{flavor_case_sensitive}}} ISO path or click on <code>...</code> to use a file manager to locate the ISO. On the third row, select your drive to be flashed. On the second row, click on <code>Write</code> when finished.

}}<!-- close tab : MacOS -->

{{Tab
|title= === Linux ===
|image=[[File:Logo-linux-500x500.png|50px]]
|content=

'''1.''' Install ''GNOME Disks''. The utility is pre-installed in ''GNOME'' desktop environment. The package is named <code>gnome-disk-utility</code>. The following example shows how to install on Debian based operating systems, but the program is also present in many other distributions.

{{Install Package|
package=gnome-disk-utility
}}

'''2.''' Launch ''GNOME Disks''.

'''Figure:''' ''GNOME Disks Xfce Launch''

[[File:GNOME-Disks-Xfce-Launch.png|600px|frameless|alt=GNOME Disks Xfce Launch|GNOME Disks Xfce Launch]]

'''3.''' Select your device present on the right tab.

'''Figure:''' ''GNOME Disk Select''

[[File:Gnome-disk-select.png.png|600px|frameless|alt=GNOME Disk Select|GNOME Disk Select]]

'''4.''' On the three dots menu on the top right side, click on <code>Restore Disk Image</code>.

'''Figure:''' ''GNOME Disk Restore Select''

[[File:GNOME-disk-restore-select.png|600px|frameless|alt=GNOME Disk Restore Select|GNOME Disk Restore Select]]

'''5.''' Click on the field of ''Image to restore'' and navigate with your file manager to select {{{project}}} ISO. After you are finished, click on <code>Start Restoring</code>.

'''Figure:''' ''GNOME Disk Restore ISO''

[[File:GNOME-Disk-restore-iso.png|600px|frameless|alt=GNOME Disk Restore ISO|GNOME Disk Restore ISO]]

'''6.''' Make sure you have selected the right device and click on <code>Restore</code>.

'''Figure:''' ''GNOME Disk Restore ISO Confirm''

[[File:Disk-restore-iso-confirm.png|600px|frameless|alt=GNOME Disk Restore ISO Confirm|GNOME Disk Restore ISO Confirm]]

'''7.''' Wait for the flashing of the ISO to finish.

'''Figure:''' ''GNOME Disk Restoring''

[[File:GNOME-Disk-Restoring.png|600px|frameless|alt=GNOME Disk Restoring|GNOME Disk Restoring]]

'''8.''' After flashing is completed, the ''Contents'' field will indicate ''ISO 9660''.

'''Figure:''' ''GNOME Disk Finish''

[[File:GNOME-Disk-finish.png|600px|frameless|alt=GNOME Disk Finish|GNOME Disk Finish]]

}}<!-- close tab : Linux -->

{{Tab
|title= === Terminal ===
|image=[[File:Utilities-terminal.png|50px]]
|content=

Note that the following steps works on Unix terminals with GNU utilities. If you are using BSD, consult your operating system documentation on how to use these tools to flash an ISO, as the utilities commands may differ (<code>dd</code> for example).

'''1.''' Find the name of your drive, substitute every reference of <code>My_own_drive</code> to your own drive ID.

{{CodeSelect|code=
ls -l /dev/disk/by-id/usb-*
}}

'''2.''' Check with <code>lsblk</code> to make sure that <code>My_own_drive</code> is '''not''' mounted (blank field under ''MOUNTPOINTS'').

{{CodeSelect|code=
lsblk /dev/disk/by-id/usb-My_own_drive
}}

'''3.''' Copy the {{{project}}} ISO to <code>My_own_drive</code>.

* Using <code>cat</code>:

{{CodeSelect|code=
sudo cp /path/to/{{{project}}}-{{{flavor_case_sensitive}}}-{{{version}}}.iso /dev/disk/by-id/usb-My_own_drive
}}
<div class="toccolours mw-collapsible mw-collapsed" data-expandtext="Learn More" data-collapsetext="Show Less">
Click on 'Learn More' on the right side for other command-line methods.
<div class="mw-collapsible-content">
* Using <code>cat</code>:

{{CodeSelect|code=
sudo cat /path/to/{{{project}}}-{{{flavor_case_sensitive}}}-{{{version}}}.iso >/dev/disk/by-id/usb-My_own_drive
}}

* Using <code>dd</code>:

{{CodeSelect|code=
sudo dd bs=4M if=/path/to/{{{project}}}-{{{flavor_case_sensitive}}}-{{{version}}}.iso of=/dev/disk/by-id/usb-My_own_drive conv=fsync oflag=direct status=progress
}}

* Using <code>tee</code>:

{{CodeSelect|code=
sudo tee </path/to/{{{project}}}-{{{flavor_case_sensitive}}}-{{{version}}}.iso >/dev/disk/by-id/usb-My_own_drive
}}

* Using <code>pv</code>:

{{CodeSelect|code=
sudo pv /path/to/{{{project}}}-{{{flavor_case_sensitive}}}-{{{version}}}.iso >/dev/disk/by-id/usb-My_own_drive
}}

</div>
</div>

'''4.''' Ensure buffers are fully written to the device before removing it.

{{CodeSelect|code=
sudo sync
}}

}}<!-- close tab : Linux -->

}}<!-- close tab controller : operating system choice -->

